"and mamma is constantly with her. She likes 
mamma better than me. Mamma listens to her a 
great deal and talks to her a little — I can't do either 
when we are alone. I don't know what she says — 
I mean what mamma says; what Blanche says I 
know as well as if I heard it. We see nothing of 
Captain Lovelock, and mamma tells me she has not 
spoken of him for two days. She thinks this is a bet- 
